<!-- SECTION 2: OVERVIEW / INTRO + TL;DR -->
<section class="content-section" id="overview-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Family Business Registration in Delhi - Overview</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
                    <p><strong>&#128204; TL;DR - Family Business Services at a Glance</strong></p>
                    <p>Family business registration in India is not a single filing - it is the formalisation of a family's commercial operations and inter-generational succession through a multi-vehicle stack: HUF (for Hindu, Sikh, Jain, Buddhist families), family-controlled Pvt Ltd or LLP for the operating business, private family trust under the Indian Trusts Act 1882, family constitution as governance and succession instruments (wills, shareholders' agreements). Income Tax Act 2025 effective 1 April 2026. Patron Delhi from INR 14,999.</p>
                </div>
                <p><div class='table-responsive-wrapper'>
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Quick Reference</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Governing Laws</td><td>Hindu Law + Hindu Succession Act 1956 (Amended 2005) + Companies Act 2013 + LLP Act 2008 + Indian Trusts Act 1882 + Income Tax Act 2025 (effective 1 April 2026)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Applicable To</td><td>Hindu, Sikh, Jain or Buddhist families (for HUF); families of all religions for the other vehicles; multi-generational families wanting governance and succession formalisation</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Timeline</td><td>Core engagement 20 to 30 working days; multi-vehicle bespoke 90 to 180 days</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Cost (Patron)</td><td>INR 14,999 fixed (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) for one primary vehicle</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>HUF Tax</td><td>Separate slab rates; basic exemption INR 3 lakh under new regime</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Daughter Rights</td><td>Equal coparcener rights as sons since 9 September 2005 per the Hindu Succession (Amendment) Act 2005</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Inheritance Tax</td><td>NONE - Estate Duty Act 1953 abolished 1985; no estate, inheritance or generational-skipping tax in India</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div></p>
                <p>Family businesses contribute approximately 79% of India's GDP, yet only 30% have formal succession plans and barely 7% of next-generation heirs are reportedly willing to step into the operating role - the gap creates significant disputes, business disruption, forced asset sales and tax inefficiency in unplanned successions. Setting up the family business correctly is a multi-vehicle exercise - HUF for ancestral and pooled assets, family-controlled Pvt Ltd or LLP for the operating business, private family trust for asset protection and multi-generational planning, family constitution for governance and succession instruments (wills, shareholders' agreements) for legal enforceability. The 2026 regulatory landscape is shaped by the Income Tax Act 2025 (effective 1 April 2026 - tax rates and slabs unchanged but the framework reorganised across 536 sections in 23 chapters) and the Hindu Succession (Amendment) Act 2005 (daughters as equal coparceners - any succession plan that excludes daughters is legally vulnerable). Patron Accounting LLP runs the family business setup from a Delhi office at INR 14,999 (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) - covering the primary work with the broader multi-vehicle engagement offered as a bespoke add-on.</p>
                <p>Content is reviewed quarterly for accuracy.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 3: WHAT IS GSTAT APPEAL FILING -->
<section class="content-section" id="what-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">What Family Business Registration in India Actually Covers</h2>
                <div class="content-text what-is-definition">
                    
                    <p>Family business registration in India is not a single regulatory filing - it is the formalisation of a family's commercial operations and inter-generational succession through a curated set of legal and tax vehicles. The five primary components are: (a) <strong>HUF (Hindu Undivided Family)</strong> - a tax-recognised separate person under Section 2(31) of the Income Tax Act, applicable to Hindu, Sikh, Jain and Buddhist families, used for holding ancestral property, pooled family assets or running a family business as a separate taxable entity at individual slab rates; (b) <strong>Family-controlled operating entity</strong> - Private Limited Company (Companies Act 2013, via SPICe+) or LLP (LLP Act 2008, via FiLLiP) with family members as shareholders or partners, often with differential voting rights under Section 43 Companies Act for control retention; (c) <strong>Private family trust</strong> under the Indian Trusts Act 1882 - the settlor (typically the patriarch or matriarch) transfers assets to trustees who hold them for the benefit of family beneficiaries; (d) <strong>Family constitution / charter</strong> - a non-binding governance document codifying decision rights, dividend policy, employment criteria, conflict resolution and exit conditions; and (e) <strong>Succession instruments</strong> - wills (under Indian Succession Act 1925), shareholders' agreements, buy-sell agreements and powers of attorney that translate the family constitution's intent into binding legal terms.</p>

<p>The 2026 regulatory framework has changed materially. The Income Tax Act 2025 came into force on 1 April 2026, replacing the Income Tax Act 1961 after 65 years - the substantive law remains largely the same (tax rates and slabs unchanged), but the structure is now 536 sections across 23 chapters (down from 800+ sections) and the terminology has changed (Previous Year and Assessment Year are now both Tax Year). For family business owners, the practical effect is that all post-1-April-2026 transactions are governed by the new Act - including HUF taxation, Section 56(2)(x) gift treatment, Section 64 clubbing provisions and Section 47 family settlement exemptions - though the substantive rules continue largely unchanged. The Hindu Succession (Amendment) Act 2005 remains the watershed - daughters have equal coparcenary rights as sons in HUF property; any succession plan that excludes or undervalues a daughter's share is legally vulnerable to challenge.</p>

<p>Delhi anchors family business engagements because of the high concentration of multi-generational family businesses in Delhi-NCR (manufacturing, real estate, healthcare, retail, hospitality and professional services), the proximity to the Registrar of Companies NCT of Delhi and Haryana, the Sub-Registrar offices for trust deed and will registration, and the broader family business advisory ecosystem (estate planning counsel, mediators, family business consultants) concentrated in NCR. Patron's Delhi office runs the full multi-vehicle stack from one engagement.</p>

                </div>
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
                    <p><strong>Key Terms for Family Business:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>HUF (Hindu Undivided Family):</strong> A family business structure unique to Indian law; separate person under Section 2(31) Income Tax Act; applicable to Hindu, Sikh, Jain, Buddhist families.</p>
<p><strong>Karta:</strong> The manager of the HUF; women can be Karta since Sujata Sharma vs Manu Gupta (2016).</p>
<p><strong>Coparceners:</strong> HUF members with birthright in HUF property; daughters equal to sons since the 2005 amendment.</p>
<p><strong>Hindu Succession (Amendment) Act 2005:</strong> Daughters as equal coparceners effective 9 September 2005.</p>
<p><strong>Family Constitution / Charter:</strong> Non-binding governance document; codifies values, decision rights, dividend policy, employment criteria, conflict resolution, exit conditions.</p>
<p><strong>Private Family Trust:</strong> Trust under Indian Trusts Act 1882; discretionary or specific (determinate); for asset protection and multi-generational planning.</p>
<p><strong>Income Tax Act 2025:</strong> Effective 1 April 2026; replaces Income Tax Act 1961; 536 sections; Tax Year terminology; rates unchanged.</p>
<p><strong>No Estate / Inheritance Tax:</strong> India abolished estate duty in 1985; no inheritance, estate or generational-skipping tax.</p>

                </div>
            </div>
