<!-- SECTION 4: WHO CAN FILE -->
<section class="content-section" id="who-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Which Family Business Setup Suits Your Situation</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <p>The right combination depends on family composition, religion, business scale and succession objectives. Patron family business registration is HIGH-VALUE for:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Multi-generational families:</strong> Operating business at INR 5+ crore turnover with 2+ generations involved or expected to be involved in business decisions.</li>
                    <li><strong>Hindu / Sikh / Jain / Buddhist families with ancestral property:</strong> Eligible for HUF formation for separate-PAN tax treatment at individual slab rates.</li>
                    <li><strong>Founder approaching transition (60+ years):</strong> Next generation has joined or is about to join; family constitution + wills + shareholders' agreement bundle becomes critical.</li>
                    <li><strong>Multi-branch family businesses:</strong> Multiple operating businesses or family arms wanting to formalise inter-branch boundaries; needs family holding company structure + branch operating companies + family council.</li>
                    <li><strong>Families planning estate distribution:</strong> Among children or grandchildren where intestate succession would create disputes.</li>
                    <li><strong>Listed family businesses (NSE / BSE):</strong> SEBI promoter group disclosures, Takeover Regulation triggers and Regulation 30 disclosure obligations need careful structuring.</li>
                    <li><strong>Non-Hindu families (Christian, Parsi, Muslim):</strong> HUF not applicable; use family Pvt Ltd or LLP + family constitution + private trust + wills combination.</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:16px;"><strong>Limited value for:</strong> Solo founders without family involvement; family businesses under INR 1 crore turnover where operational scale does not justify formal governance vehicles; families not ready to engage on succession (constitution requires active multi-generational participation); families with serious unresolved disputes (mediation first, formalisation second).</p>

            </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

