<!-- SECTION 8: DOCUMENTS REQUIRED -->
<section class="content-section" id="documents-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Documents Checklist for Family Business Registration</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <ul>
                    <li>PAN and Aadhaar of all family members (adults and minors with PAN)</li>
                    <li>Family tree document showing relationships (helpful for HUF coparcener identification and succession mapping)</li>
                    <li>Religion declaration of each family member (relevant for HUF eligibility - Hindu, Sikh, Jain, Buddhist)</li>
                    <li>List of current family business entities (proprietorship, partnership, LLP, Pvt Ltd, Public Ltd) with PAN, GSTIN, CIN or LLPIN</li>
                    <li>List of family assets - movable (bank, MF, demat, business interests) and immovable (residential, commercial, agricultural) with valuations</li>
                    <li>Existing family arrangements - any partition deeds, gift deeds, family settlement agreements, wills</li>
                    <li>Income tax returns of family members for the last 3 years (for HUF capital pooling and gift / clubbing analysis)</li>
                    <li>Delhi registered office or residential address proofs for entity setup</li>
                    <li>Marriage certificates for spouse-coparcener identification (for HUF and succession)</li>
                    <li>For private family trust - intended settlor, trustees, beneficiaries (with PAN), trust corpus assets, distribution preferences</li>
                    <li>For family constitution - founder's stated values, ownership philosophy, employment criteria preferences, dividend policy expectations</li>
                    <li>For NRI / OCI family members - residency status, jurisdictional considerations, FEMA position on Indian asset holdings</li>
                </ul>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Common Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Daughter coparcener rights post-2005 amendment</td><td>Many older family business setups (pre-2005 or assuming the pre-amendment position) have succession plans that undervalue or exclude daughters; any such plan is legally vulnerable to challenge.</td><td>Patron maps daughter coparceners at engagement start under the amended Section 6 position - daughters have equal birthright in HUF property as sons. Existing succession plans are re-examined; necessary partition deeds, family settlement deeds or supplementary documents are drafted to bring the plan into compliance.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Section 56(2)(x) gift treatment</td><td>Receipt of property without consideration above INR 50,000 from non-relatives is taxable; the "relatives" definition is restrictive - cousins, nephews, nieces and in-laws beyond brother / sister of spouse are NOT relatives.</td><td>Patron maps family relationships against the Section 56(2)(x) Explanation definition - gifts among defined relatives are tax-free; structures like trusts, genuine commercial loans or graduated transfers route around the trigger for extended relatives.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Section 64 clubbing on HUF capital pooling</td><td>Income from assets transferred to spouse, son's wife, minor child or HUF without adequate consideration is clubbed in the transferor's hands; this catches HUF capital pooling and intra-family transfers.</td><td>Patron structures HUF capital pooling carefully - HUF corpus from inherited property or gifts from non-members (e.g., gifts from a grandparent to the HUF) does not trigger Section 64(2). Initial HUF corpus typically comes from ancestral property or gifts from outside coparcener members.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Family constitution non-binding nature</td><td>The family constitution document is not legally enforceable; family members can ignore it; only the underlying legal instruments (shareholders' agreement, wills, trust deeds) carry enforceability.</td><td>Patron treats the family constitution as the OPERATING GUIDE and translates its key provisions into legally binding instruments at the same engagement - shareholders' agreement, buy-sell agreement, voting agreement, wills and trust deeds. The constitution sets the WHY; the binding documents set the HOW.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>SEBI Takeover Regulations for listed family businesses</td><td>Any promoter group restructuring in a listed company triggers SEBI (SAST) Regulations 2011 disclosure obligations and possible mandatory open offer; catches family restructurings that move shareholding between branches.</td><td>For listed family businesses, Patron routes every promoter group movement through SEBI compliance - Regulation 30 disclosure thresholds, Regulation 29 transfers between persons forming part of the promoter group, Regulation 10 exemptions for intra-promoter transfers.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Income Tax Act 2025 transition (effective 1 April 2026)</td><td>All post-1-April-2026 transactions are now governed by the new Act; HUF setups, gift treatment under Section 56(2)(x), clubbing under Section 64 and family settlement under Section 47 are reorganised under renumbered sections though substantive rules continue largely unchanged.</td><td>Patron ensures HUF tax filings, gift treatment, clubbing exposure and family settlement structuring are all aligned with the new framework from day one - Tax Year terminology, renumbered sections and the Income Tax Rules 2026.</td></tr>

                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

