<section id="faq-section" class="content-section" style="background-color: #ffffff;">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <div class="faq-expanded">
                <aside class="faq-expanded__aside">
                    <h2 class="faq-expanded__title">FAQs: Family Business Registration in Delhi</h2>
                    <p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about Family Business Registration for Delhi businesses, answered by our CA and CS team.</p>
                    @include('partials.faq-enquiry-form', ['enquiryLocation' => 'Delhi', 'enquiryService' => 'Family Business Registration in Delhi'])
                </aside>
                <div class="faq-expanded__list">
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the best legal structure for a family business in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Family business in India is rarely a single structure - the right setup is typically a combination of HUF (Hindu Undivided Family for Hindu, Sikh, Jain or Buddhist families holding ancestral property), family-controlled Pvt Ltd or LLP (operating entity with limited liability and equity flexibility), private family trust (asset protection and multi-generational holding), family constitution (non-binding governance) and succession instruments (wills, shareholders' agreements). Family size, religion, business scale and succession objectives drive the specific combination.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How do you register a Hindu Undivided Family (HUF) for business?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>HUF is created automatically by Hindu Law on a happening of event (marriage typically); no statutory deed required for formation. For practical operations, an HUF Deed is drafted naming the Karta and coparceners. PAN is applied for the HUF separately via Form 49A on the Income Tax e-filing portal (free). A bank account is opened in the HUF name with the Karta as the signatory. The HUF then files separate income tax returns and is taxed at individual slab rates.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Do daughters have equal rights in HUF property after the 2005 amendment?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Yes. The Hindu Succession (Amendment) Act 2005 (effective 9 September 2005) gave daughters equal coparcenary rights as sons in HUF property; daughters have birthright in HUF property and can demand partition. The Supreme Court in Vineeta Sharma vs Rakesh Sharma (2020) clarified that daughters have these rights regardless of whether the father was alive on the date of the 2005 amendment. The only protection - dispositions or partitions before 20 December 2004 are preserved.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is a family constitution and is it legally binding in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>A family constitution (or family charter) is a non-binding governance document that codifies the family's values, decision rights, dividend policy, employment criteria for family members, conflict resolution mechanisms, succession framework and exit conditions. It is NOT legally enforceable on its own. To make its provisions binding, the family constitution's key provisions are translated into legally binding instruments - shareholders' agreement, buy-sell agreement, voting agreement, individual wills and trust deeds.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How does the new Income Tax Act 2025 affect family businesses?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>The Income Tax Act 2025 (effective 1 April 2026) replaces the Income Tax Act 1961. Tax rates and slabs are unchanged. The Act has 536 sections across 23 chapters (down from 800+) with renumbered sections. For family businesses, the substantive rules on HUF taxation, Section 56(2)(x) gifts, Section 64 clubbing and Section 47 family settlement remain largely the same but appear under renumbered sections. Previous Year and Assessment Year are now both Tax Year.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Is gift to family members taxable in India under Section 56(2)(x)?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Receipt of property without consideration above INR 50,000 from a non-relative is taxable. Relatives defined in the Explanation include spouse, brother or sister, brother or sister of spouse, brother or sister of either parent and any lineal ascendant or descendant - gifts among these defined relatives are tax-free. Cousins, nephews, nieces and in-laws beyond brother or sister of spouse are NOT relatives for this purpose and gifts to them above INR 50,000 are taxable. The provision continues under Income Tax Act 2025.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the difference between HUF and a Private Family Trust?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>HUF is a creature of Hindu Law applicable only to Hindu, Sikh, Jain or Buddhist families; coparceners have birthright; daughters have equal rights since 2005; income taxed at individual slab rates. Private family trust under Indian Trusts Act 1882 is available to all religions; settlor decides beneficiaries and trustees; trust can be discretionary or specific; taxation differs - discretionary trust at maximum marginal rate, specific trust at beneficiaries' individual slab rates.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Is there an inheritance or estate tax in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>No. India has no estate, inheritance or generational-skipping tax. The Estate Duty Act 1953 was abolished in 1985. Assets transferred by will or intestate succession attract no tax in either the transferor or the recipient. Only future income from the inherited assets is taxable in the recipient's hands at applicable slab rates. This makes structured succession planning materially more tax-efficient in India than in many Western jurisdictions where estate or inheritance taxes apply.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Quick Answers -->
            <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:32px;">
                <p><strong>Quick Answers</strong></p>
                <p><strong>Q: Multi-vehicle approach?</strong> A: HUF + Pvt Ltd or LLP + Private Trust + Family Constitution + Wills - five vehicles typically combine.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: HUF eligibility?</strong> A: Hindu, Sikh, Jain, Buddhist families only - based on Hindu Law.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Daughter coparcener rights?</strong> A: Equal to sons since the Hindu Succession (Amendment) Act 2005 - effective 9 September 2005.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Karta?</strong> A: Manager of HUF - traditionally eldest male; women can be Karta since Sujata Sharma vs Manu Gupta (2016).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: HUF formation?</strong> A: Automatic by Hindu Law on event; HUF Deed for bank / tax practicality; PAN via Form 49A (FREE).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Family Pvt Ltd?</strong> A: Pvt Ltd via SPICe+; differential voting rights under Section 43 Companies Act 2013 for control retention.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Private Family Trust?</strong> A: Under Indian Trusts Act 1882; settlor + trustees + beneficiaries; discretionary or specific.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Family Constitution?</strong> A: Non-binding governance document; legally enforceable through aligned shareholders' agreement, wills, trust deeds.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Inheritance tax in India?</strong> A: NONE - India has no estate, inheritance or generational-skipping tax (abolished 1985).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Section 56(2)(x)?</strong> A: Gifts from non-relatives above INR 50,000 taxable; relatives definition is restrictive.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Income Tax Act 2025?</strong> A: Effective 1 April 2026; 536 sections; Tax Year terminology; rates unchanged.</p>
